Document: ParticleProcessMaterial properties
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: This section explains how the Min, Max, and Curve properties of ParticleProcessMaterial control particle behavior over their lifetime.
The properties in this material control how particles behave and change over their lifetime. A lot of them have Min, Max, and Curve values that allow you to fine-tune their behavior. The relationship between these values is this: When a particle is spawned, the property is set with a random value between Min and Max. If Min and Max are the same, the value will always be the same for every particle. If the Curve is also set, the value of the property will be multiplied by the value of the curve at the current point in a particle's lifetime. Use the curve to change a property over the particle lifetime. Very complex behavior can be expressed this way.
Note: This page covers how to use ParticleProcessMaterial for 2D scenes specifically. For information on how to use it in a 3D scene see Process material properties.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Process Material 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: Explains the Lifetime Randomness property for 2D particle systems.
Lifetime Randomness
The Lifetime Randomness property controls how much randomness to apply to each particle's lifetime. A value of 0 means there is no randomness at all and all particles live for the same amount of time, set by the Lifetime property. A value of 1 means that a particle's lifetime is completely random within the range of [0.0, Lifetime].
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Process Material 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: This section describes the particle flags available in the ParticleProcessMaterial for 2D particles.

Particle Flags
^^^^^^^^^^^^

The ParticleProcessMaterial has a set of flags that can be enabled to modify particle behavior. These flags are:

*   **Align to direction**: When enabled, particles will rotate to face the direction they are moving in. This is useful for effects like rain or shooting projectiles.
*   **Friction**: When enabled, particles will experience friction, slowing them down over time. The amount of friction is determined by the `friction` property.
*   **Bounce**: When enabled, particles will bounce off surfaces. The amount of bounce is determined by the `bounce` property.
*   **Disable gravity**: When enabled, particles will not be affected by gravity. This is useful for effects where you want particles to float or move independently of the world's gravity.
*   **Disable_X**: When enabled, particles will not move along the X-axis.
*   **Disable_Y**: When enabled, particles will not move along the Y-axis.
*   **Disable_Z**: When enabled, particles will not move along the Z-axis. (Note: This flag is typically not relevant for 2D particles, but is included for consistency with the 3D particle system).

These flags provide a powerful way to fine-tune the behavior of your particle systems, allowing for a wide range of visual effects.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Process Material 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: This section describes the spawn properties of a 2D particle process material in Godot.

Spawn
-----

The Spawn section controls how particles are generated.

.. rst-class:: table-and-heading

.. csv-table::
   :header: Name,Type,Description,Default

   `spawn_shape`,"enum",Shape of the spawn area.,0
   `spawn_shape_circle_radius`,"float",Radius of the circle if `spawn_shape` is Circle.,0.0
   `spawn_shape_circle_points`,"int",Number of points to use for the circle if `spawn_shape` is Circle.,16
   `spawn_shape_box_extents`,"Vector2",Size of the box if `spawn_shape` is Box.,(1,1)
   `spawn_shape_points`,"PackedVector2Array",Array of points if `spawn_shape` is Points.,[]
   `spawn_shape_points_count`,"int",Number of points to randomly pick from `spawn_shape_points` if `spawn_shape` is Points.,1

`spawn_shape`
    Shape of the spawn area. Options are:
    *   Box
    *   Circle
    *   Points

`spawn_shape_circle_radius`
    Radius of the circle if `spawn_shape` is Circle.

`spawn_shape_circle_points`
    Number of points to use for the circle if `spawn_shape` is Circle. This affects the smoothness of the circle's edge.

`spawn_shape_box_extents`
    Size of the box if `spawn_shape` is Box.

`spawn_shape_points`
    Array of points if `spawn_shape` is Points. Particles will spawn at these specific locations.

`spawn_shape_points_count`
    Number of points to randomly pick from `spawn_shape_points` if `spawn_shape` is Points. If set to 0, all points will be used.
---CHUNK---
