Document: particle_process_material_2d.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: This section explains how to configure particle flipbook animations for linear playback or random texture selection in Godot's particle systems.
Animation
Note: Particle flipbook animation is only effective if the CanvasItemMaterial used on the GPUParticles2D or CPUParticles2D node has been configured accordingly.

To set up the particle flipbook for linear playback, set the Speed Min and Speed Max values to 1.

By default, looping is disabled. If the particle is done playing before its lifetime ends, the particle will keep using the flipbook's last frame. If looping is enabled, the animation will loop back to the first frame and resume playing.

The relationship between particle lifetime, animation speed, and number of images in the sprite sheet is as follows:
Note: At an animation speed of 1.0, the animation will reach the last image in the sequence just as the particle's lifetime ends.
Animation FPS = Number of images / Lifetime

If you wish the particle flipbook to be used as a source of random particle textures for every particle, keep the speed values at 0 and set Offset Max to 1 instead.

The GPUParticles2D node's Fixed FPS also affects animation playback. For smooth animation playback, it's recommended to set it to 0 so that the particle is simulated on every rendered frame. If this is not an option for your use case, set Fixed FPS to be equal to the effective framerate used by the flipbook animation.
---CHUNK---
Document: ParticleProcessMaterial2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use textures as emission masks for GPUParticles2D nodes.

Emission Shapes
ParticleProcessMaterials allow you to set an Emission Mask, which dictates the area and direction in which particles are emitted. These can be generated from textures in your project.

To set an emission mask, ensure that a ParticleProcessMaterial is assigned to the GPUParticles2D node and that the GPUParticles2D node is selected. A "Particles" menu will appear in the Toolbar.

Click on the "Particles" menu and select "Load Emission Mask". Then, choose the texture you want to use as your mask from the file dialog. After selecting the texture, a dialog box will appear with several settings to configure the emission mask.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Process Material 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: Describes the different emission mask types available for 2D particle systems.
Emission Mask
Three types of emission masks can be generated from a texture:
*   Solid Pixels: Particles will spawn from any area of the texture, excluding transparent areas.
*   Border Pixels: Particles will spawn from the outer edges of the texture.
*   Directed Border Pixels: Similar to Border Pixels, but adds extra information to the mask to give particles the ability to emit away from the borders. Note that an Initial Velocity will need to be set in order to utilize this.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Process Material 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use emission colors with particle materials, specifically the "Capture from Pixel" option and the implications of using the "Load Emission Mask" menu.
Emission Colors
"Capture from Pixel" will cause the particles to inherit the color of the mask at their spawn points. Once you click "OK", the mask will be generated and set to the ParticleProcessMaterial, under Spawn and then Position. All of the values within this section have been automatically generated by the "Load Emission Mask" menu, so they should generally be left alone. Note: An image should not be added to Point Texture or Color Texture directly. The "Load Emission Mask" menu should always be used instead.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Process Material 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_process_material_2d.rst
Summary: This section explains how to convert a ParticleProcessMaterial to a ShaderMaterial to customize shader code.

To change or implement new behaviors in shader code, you can convert the current ParticleProcessMaterial to a ShaderMaterial. Existing properties are preserved during the conversion. Enabled features will also affect the converted shader code.

To convert the material, right-click on the material in the FileSystem dock and select **Convert to ShaderMaterial**. Alternatively, you can right-click on any property in the inspector that holds a reference to the material and choose the same conversion option.